question:
Find $M^2+(A^T\cdot B)^{-1}$, where $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 3 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 4 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
7 & 2 & 1 \\
-1 & 3 & 0  \\
2 & 0 & -2 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find ${\left(C^T \cdot B-6 \cdot I^{-1}\right)}^2$, where $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 0 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$, $C=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
3 & 3 & 1 \\ 
1 & -2 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, and $I$  -- identity matrix.

Consider the following statements: 
S1:  If $A$ is a $4 \times 4$ matrix such that $\mathrm{det}=-2$, then $\mathrm{det} \left( 2 A^T A^{-1} \right)=16$; 
S2: Let $A$ be an $m \times n$ matrix. If the equation $A\textbf{x}=\textbf{0}$ has only the trivial solution $x \in \mathbb{R}^n$, then the columns of $A$ are linearly independent.

Indicate which of the following is a linear combination of $A=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      3& 2\\
			0 & 1 
    \end{array}\right]$, $B=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      0& -1 \\
			1 & 2 
    \end{array}\right]$ and $C=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      5& 4 \\
			-1 & 0
    \end{array}\right]$.
